               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melb. bot. Garden, ¶ 24/4/62 ¶ Dear Sir William. ¶  ¶ I have to acknowledge your friendly communications of 3 different dates by last mail, ¶  and am obliged indeed for all the interest you continue t...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">62.04.24f</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To William Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Directors' letters, vol. LXXV, Australian and Pacific letters 1859-65, letter no. 149.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS black-edged; M's sister Bertha died on 7 September 1861.</p>
               </note>Melb. bot. Garden,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">24/4/62</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dear Sir William.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have to acknowledge your friendly communications of 3 different dates by last mail,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Letters not found.</p>
               </note> and am obliged indeed for all the interest you continue to evince towards my labours &amp; for your manyfold tokens of kindness, crowned by the dedication of the last truly splendid vol of the bot. Magazine, a kindness which I shall ever vividly bear in mind &amp; for which I repeat my best thanks.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See notes to M to W. Hooker, 24 March 1862 (in this edition as 62-03-24b).</p>
               </note> I send a few novelties — <name key="Symplocos">Symplocos</name> will interest you. I think Dr Wights view is best, to place the <name key="Symploceae">Symploceae</name> near <name key="Caprifoliaceae">Caprifoliaceae</name> or near some order allied to <name key="Myrtaceae">Myrtaceae</name>.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The systematic position of <name key="Symplocos">Symplocos</name>, in Styraceae, is discussed in Wight (1846-51), vol. 2, p. 37, where its closeness to Ebenaceae is emphasised. The nature of the genus is discussed in Wight (1840–53), vol. 4, pp. 10 -11, without assessing its broader systematic position.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>From Mr Bentham I have not heard during the last two or three mails. Probably he is on the continent.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">From the time Bentham wrote to M on16 November 1861, except for the period 23 December 1861 to 7 January 1862 he was in London working at Kew and at the British Museum (acknowledged in M to G. Bentham, 24 January 1862) until August 1862 (RBG Kew, Bentham diary, Ms. 17, 1861-5. BEN).</p>
               </note> I feel however sure, that after the arrival of my first consignment of plants, which must have now reached him, I shall enjoy monthly his communications. I am for instance not quite certain in what succession he may require the various orders of <name key="Thalamiflorae">Thalamiflorae</name>, which are so numerous. The fourth case will go by the "Orwell" this week &amp; contains</p>
